# Semgrep ignore file for django-deep
# 
# This file documents why certain security warnings are acceptable:
#
# 1. Custom Expression Extensions (extends-custom-expression):
#    - All custom expressions (JsonExtract, ConcatValuesSubquery, etc.) use Django's
#      parameter binding system via the `extra` dictionary
#    - Django automatically escapes all parameters passed through `extra` to prevent SQL injection
#    - User inputs are validated through Django's ORM queryset system before reaching these expressions
#    - The `data_path` parameter in JsonExtract is processed through controlled transformation
#      methods (get_data_postgresql, get_data_default) that only perform string splitting/joining
#
# 2. Custom Expression as_sql (custom-expression-as-sql):
#    - The `as_sql()` method calls use Django's built-in parameter binding
#    - All user-provided values are passed as bound parameters, not raw SQL strings
#    - Django's ORM ensures proper escaping of all parameters
#
# These warnings are false positives because Django's ORM provides built-in SQL injection
# protection through parameter binding. However, developers should still:
# - Never pass raw SQL strings directly
# - Always use Django's ORM methods and parameter binding
# - Validate user inputs before passing them to these expressions

